<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-08-07T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-08-07T04:00:00-05:00" n="659" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d659">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861a.01/60: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-08-07T18:00:00+09:00"><hi rend="italic">August 7,
                                        1921—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received August 7—5:32
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>265. Legation at Peking sends following telegram to be repeated to
                            Department as its no. 282, August 7, noon.</p>
                        <p>Japan now ready to negotiate, says Yourin.<note n="17" xml:id="d659fn17">Ignatius Yurin, president of the mission of the Far Eastern
                                Republic to China.</note> Form of negotiations dependent upon
                            American interest in them. Yourin will have to concede more if the
                            United States does not take such interest.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>